<br>
I did just what you are planning on doing. Had Cable for awhile but was paying out wazo to get 3 comps on the net. Got DSL and a router and now I have 7 comps on the same DSL line. I went through afew routers before I got it working right. So here is what I have and why....<br>
<br>
First off... I wouldnt go with wireless. They work near the same as cordless phones. So if you have a corldless phone or you neighbor 5 houses down has one it can make the signal get wierd.<br>
<br>
As far as normal routers go, first I went with Linksys and had some problems setting it up. It wasnt very self explanitory. I then went with D-Link and had the same problems that I had with the linksys. Finally got  a Barricade from SMC and had it up and running in about 10 min. The SMC was a little bit more expensive then the others but it works perfectly.<br>
<br>
The way it works is this. When you order the DSL you need to get the ethernet version of the modem. Single users usually get a USB modem. I have found that most ISP's with offer a networking internet solution, thats the modem you need.<br>
<br>
When you get DSL, you will get the modem and the connection software/drives. DONT install the software/drivers. Hook the modem to the modem port on the router and the comps to the ethernet ports. In the router manual there will be an IP address for the router, now from your PC open IE or netscape and type in the IP address you found in the manual ( should be something like 192.168.123.256 ) Now a web based page should come up allowing you to config the router. Just plug in your login and pass from your ISP and walla.<br>
<br>
Only problem what can happen at this point is if you have your old software/drives from your old ISP installed. You just need to completely remove all of them and it will work fine.<br>
<br>
Anyways heres the model of the router I have..<br>
<br>
SMC7008BR Barricade 8 Port 10/100 Broudband Router<br>
<br>
Site is www.smc.com<br>
<br>
