<br>
So contact your provider and ask how to share the connection with another device, technically it doesn't matter to the modem and the service what you connect to it.  With DSL you are getting a fixed amount of bandwith to the modem, what you do with it after it leaves the modem is your concern.  <br>
<br>
Internet conection sharing and a hub is the cheapest method to share your connection with another computer.  You will need a hub (cheap), a 2nd nic for the connection sharing computer (cheap), and some wire (cheap).  Downside is internet connection sharing can be troublesome to configure. <br>
<br>
Cable modem identifies the system connected to it as a valid device on network and the DHCP server gives it an IP address.  Because of this a router is often a good solution here.  Just inform your ISP what the MAC address is or configure the router with the needed information to be recognized as a device on the network and there you go.  The computers that connect to the router get their IP address and settings from the router or are preconfigured so that the router sees and communicates with them.  Easy to set up and that, but a router is much more expensive than the internet connection sharing is.   <p><a href="http://silverdaggers.freehosting.net">
